{"questionId":"21829","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>An inclined railway travels along a straight track on a steep hill, as shown in the diagram.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/227ca67715aea1e867147006e30e95b52898fec5.png\"></p>\n<p>The locations of the stations on the railway can be described by coordinates in reference&nbsp;to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>y</mi></math>, and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi></math>-axes, where the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math> axes are in the horizontal plane and the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi></math>-axis&nbsp;is vertical.</p>\n<p>The ground level station <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext></math> has coordinates <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>140</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>)</mo></math> and station <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>B</mtext></math>, located near the top&nbsp;of the hill, has coordinates <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>250</mn><mo>)</mo></math>. All coordinates are given in metres.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Station <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>M</mtext></math> is to be built halfway between stations <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>B</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the coordinates of station <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>M</mtext></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempt at substitution in the midpoint formula &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>140</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>20</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>15</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>250</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>80</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>125</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><br>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"21829","referenceCode":"21M.1.SL.TZ2.2b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the coordinates of station M.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.1—3d space, volume, angles, midpoints"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}